Today, #DDay75thAnniversary, we remember those who went to Normandy, and the cause for which they sacrificed.

That cause was not the destruction of Germany. Today, we count the German people as friends.

Hate, fear, intolerance, exclusion, cruelty—this is the true enemy.

They sacrificed in their cause. Eleanor Roosevelt wrote that "They may never go beyond the water or the beach, but all their lives, perhaps, they will bear the marks of this day. At that, they will be fortunate, for many others won't return."
They didn't fight for the glory of America. They fought for each other, for our allies, and our fellow human beings. They fought to make other people free. In this, they embodied the best of America.

Americans came to France as liberators, not conquerors. They fought to oppose what Churchill called a "monstrous tyranny." They came to put an end to nationalist regimes; to stop the horrors that are the inevitable result of politics that elevate one group above another.

President Roosevelt said that "these men are lately drawn from the ways of peace. They fight not for the lust of conquest. They fight to end conquest. They fight to liberate. They fight to let justice arise, and tolerance and good will among all Thy people."
75 years ago today, thousands of young men crossed the English Channel into Normandy. Many would die there. To them, today and every day, we owe our thanks. #DDay75thAnniversary

Soldiers, Sailors, and Airmen of the Allied Expeditionary Force!
